<h1>@HI{{ha}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong> ... 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong> is used to indicate information about something that has already been introduced
or about which the speaker is expected to know.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong> is used to mark a topic, which is then explained or described in the rest of the
sentence.
</p>

<p>
The sentence pattern @N1{{}}<strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong>@N2{{}}@HI{{ga}} selects @N1{{}} as a topic about which a 
quality or property, @N2{{}}, is explained.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong> is used to indicate a contrast.
sentence.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{asokoni@KJ{{red}}i@KJ{{book}}gaarimasune. are <strong>ha</strong>@KJ{{sino-^character}}no@KJ{{book}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Over there is a red book. It's a kanji book.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{private}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{study}}@KJ{{exam}}@HI{{de<strong>ha</strong>}}
      @KJ{{in}}@KJ{{country}}@KJ{{word}}@HI{{ga}} @KJ{{learn}}@HI{{emasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      In my school we can learn Chinese.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{elephant}}<strong>ha</strong>@KJ{{nose}}ga@KJ{{long}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The elephant has a long nose.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kinou<strong>ha</strong>}}@KJ{{mountain}}@HI{{ga}}@KJ{{see}}@HI{{emashitaga,}}
      @HI{{kyou<strong>ha</strong>}}@KJ{{see}}@HI{{emasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yesterday we could see mountains but today we can't.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When <strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong> follows a noun + @HI{{ga}} or noun + @HI{{wo}}, <strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong>
replaces those particles. For all other particles, <strong>@HI{{ha}}</strong> follows them rather than
replacing them.
</p>

